'''[[Cannabis]] in [[Jordan]]''' is illegal.

==History==
In the mid-20th century, Jordan (then [[Emirate of Transjordan|Trans-Jordan]]) was noted as a smuggling route, carrying hashish from Turkey, Iran, Lebanon, and Syria into Egypt.<ref name="Plascov2017">{{cite book|author=Avi Plascov|title=The Palestinian Refugees in Jordan 1948-1957|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lzgkDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT117|date=18 May 2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-351-66747-0|pages=117–}}</ref><ref name="FletcherFletcher2015">{{cite book|author1=Robert Fletcher|author2=Robert S. G. Fletcher|title=British Imperialism and 'the Tribal Question': Desert Administration and Nomadic Societies in the Middle East, 1919-1936|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tSRUBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA139|year=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-872931-0|pages=139–}}</ref><ref name="PhilippSchäbler1998">{{cite book|author1=Thomas Philipp|author2=Birgit Schäbler|title=The Syrian Land: Processes of Integration and Fragmentation : Bilād Al-Shām from the 18th to the 20th Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B-iDgNPVuhAC&pg=PA383|year=1998|publisher=Franz Steiner Verlag|isbn=978-3-515-07309-7|pages=383–}}</ref> In 1937 the total of all drugs seized in Jordan was just 6 kilograms of hashish. [[Sherif Nasser]], uncle of the king of Jordan, was credibly implicated in cannabis smuggling.<ref name="Buxton2011">{{cite book|author=Julia Buxton|title=The Politics of Narcotic Drugs: A Survey|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sYJaBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA34|date=6 April 2011|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-88061-2|pages=34–}}</ref>

