{{Food safety}} '''FAT TOM''' is a [[mnemonic device]] used in the [[food service]] industry to describe the six favorable conditions required for the growth of [[foodborne pathogens]]. It is an [[acronym]] for '''food, acidity, time, temperature, oxygen''' and '''moisture'''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Servsafe Essentials Fifth Edition|year=2008|isbn=978-1-58280-224-4|pages=27}}</ref>
== Conditions == Each of the six conditions that foster the growth foodborne pathogens are defined in set ranges:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.extension.iastate.edu/foodsafety/Lesson/L4/L4p1.html |title=Food safety lessons: FAT TOM |publisher=[[Iowa State University]], University Extension school}}</ref>
{|style="align:center; border:1px solid black;" |- |style="width=25%; font-size: 125%;"|'''F''' |style="width=35%; font-size: 125%;"|Food |There are sufficient nutrients available that promote the growth of microorganisms. Protein-rich foods, such as meat, milk, eggs and fish are most susceptible. |- |style="font-size: 125%;"|'''A''' |style="font-size: 125%;"|Acidity |Foodborne pathogens require a slightly acidic pH level of 4.6-7.5, while they thrive in conditions with a pH of 6.6-7.5. The United States [[Food and Drug Administration]]'s (FDA) regulations for acid/acidified foods require that the food be brought to pH 4.5 or below. |- |style="font-size: 125%;"|'''T''' |style="font-size: 125%;"|Time |Food should be removed from "the danger zone" (see below) within two-four hours, either by cooling or heating. While most guidelines state two hours, a few indicate four hours is still safe. |- |style="font-size: 125%;"|'''T''' |style="font-size: 125%;"|Temperature |Food-borne pathogens grow best in temperatures between {{convert|41|to|135|F|C}}, a range referred to as the temperature danger zone (TDZ). They thrive in temperatures that are between {{convert|70|to|104|F|C}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fsis.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsis/topics/food-safety-education/get-answers/food-safety-fact-sheets/safe-food-handling/danger-zone-40-f-140-f/ |title="Danger Zone" (40 °F - 140 °F) |publisher=US Department of Agriculture |accessdate=14 October 2015}}</ref> |- |style="font-size: 125%;"|'''O''' |style="font-size: 125%;"|Oxygen |Almost all foodborne pathogens are aerobic, that is requiring oxygen to grow. Some pathogens, such as ''[[Clostridium botulinum]]'', the source of botulism, are anaerobic. |- |style="font-size: 125%;"|'''M''' |style="font-size: 125%;"|Moisture |Water is essential for the growth of foodborne pathogens, [[water activity]] (a<sub>w</sub>) is a measure of the water available for use and is measured on a scale of 0 to 1.0. Foodborne pathogens grow best in foods that have a<sub>w</sub> between 0.95 and 1.0. FDA regulations for canned foods require a<sub>w</sub> of 0.85 or below. |- |}
